E.COLI, HEMOLYTIC UREMIC SYNDROME - USA (GEORGIA) (02)
******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
E. coli, hemolytic uremic syndrome - USA (Georgia) 980626234520
[1
Date: Tue, 30 Jun 1998 07:24:12 -0400
From: Robert A. LaBudde <ral@lcfltd.com>
Source: FSNET and news media [Exerpts - ES

Swimming pool operators and health officials in the Washington [D.C. area
were cited as emphasizing yesterday that they take strict precautions to
prevent contamination of pools, after public worries were aroused by an
unusual outbreak of a potentially lethal _E. coli_ bacterium at a suburban
Atlanta water park.
Five toddlers were hospitalized, with two in critical condition, after
developing the most serious form of _Escherichia coli_ infection in
Georgia. Eight others were sick as well, all after swimming in a pool in
which authorities believe an infected child defecated.
In response to a deluge of questions, in the region and across the country,
health authorities and pool managers stressed the rarity of the outbreak.
It is only the second time _E. coli_ has been transmitted in a chlorinated
swimming pool in the United States, they said. Generally, the bacterium
spreads through tainted, undercooked meat or unwashed fruits and vegetables.
They also said that water parks and other swimming pools follow rigorous
procedures, usually including hourly checks of chlorine levels in the
water, to keep pools safe. Pools evacuate swimmers immediately if chlorine
levels fall too far or the water is fouled.
The story goes on to say that chlorine is the principal guardian against
_E. coli_ and other bacteria in pools. State or county guidelines set
levels for chlorine in pools, with a typical minimum of 1.5 parts chlorine
per million parts of water. In Maryland, the guideline for kiddie pools is
stricter, at 3 parts chlorine per million parts water. That's also the
guideline for the District's 36 pools.
